testicular veins both drain into the inferior vena cava","Varicoceles occur predominantly on the right side","The testicular veins drain via the internal iliac veins","The left testicular vein drains into the left renal vein"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Etesticular artery\u003C/strong\u003E arises from the anterior aspect of the abdominal aorta at L2, not L3. While the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright testicular vein\u003C/strong\u003E drains directly into the inferior vena cava, the \u003Cstrong\u003Eleft testicular vein\u003C/strong\u003E drains into the left renal vein. This anatomical arrangement explains why varicoceles occur more commonly on the left side (80-90% of cases), not the \u003Cstrong\u003Eright side\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EThe \u003Cstrong\u003Einternal iliac veins\u003C/strong\u003E are not involved in testicular venous drainage. The perpendicular insertion of the left testicular vein into the left renal vein, combined with increased pressure from the superior mesenteric artery crossing anterior to the left renal vein (nutcracker phenomenon), contributes to the higher prevalence of left-sided varicoceles.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["The testicular artery arises from the anterior aspect of the abdominal aorta at the level of L2.","The left testicular vein drains into the left renal vein while the right testicular vein drains directly into the inferior vena cava.","Left-sided varicoceles account for 80-90% of cases due to the perpendicular insertion of the left testicular vein into the left renal vein."],"references":["Tiwana MS, Leslie SW. Anatomy, Abdomen and Pelvis: Testes. [Updated 2023 Apr 15]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK470201/","Benzi TC, Logsdon NT, Sampaio FJB, Favorito LA. Testicular arteries anatomy applied to fowler-sthephens surgery in high undescended testis - a narrative review. Int Braz J Urol. 2022 Jan-Feb;48(1):8-17. doi: 10.1590/S1677-5538.IBJU.2021.99.11. PMID: 34003614; PMCID: PMC8691233.","Gurung P, Yetiskul E, Jialal I. Physiology, Male Reproductive System. [Updated 2023 May 1]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2024 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538429/","Ansell, I. D. (2012). Atlas of male reproductive pathology (Vol. 10). Springer Science \u0026 Business Media."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52161"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15772"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"21278"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"21278","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/21278"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2seFCYdx6YzLORJSwUQvfvIAHyxL8i.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/2seFCYdx6YzLORJSwUQvfvIAHyxL8i.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":1500,"height":1125}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"52161","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/52161"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-12-01T20:02:34+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-01T20:03:04+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"8463"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66708"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position"